  <h1>Finding and Fixing Medical Billing Errors</h1>
  <p><em>Reviewed by Aspen Lockwood (AL), Editor-in-Chief. Updated May 2026.</em></p>
  <h2>Request the itemized bill and EOB</h2><p>Get a line-item bill from the hospital and your Explanation of Benefits (EOB) from your insurer. They should tell the same story. Discrepancies are the starting point for disputes.</p>
  <h2>Common errors to look for</h2><p>Duplicate charges (same service billed twice); upcoding (CPT code billed doesn&rsquo;t match service received); unbundling (procedures that should be billed as a group billed separately at higher individual rates); wrong date of service; charges for services not received; incorrect room type; medications listed that weren&rsquo;t administered.</p>
  <h2>How to dispute</h2><p>Write a dispute letter to the billing department identifying each error by line item and procedure code. Request written confirmation of the correction within 30 days. Keep copies of everything. If the hospital refuses, escalate to the hospital&rsquo;s patient advocate or compliance office.</p>
  <h2>Involve your insurer</h2><p>If the error affected your insurer&rsquo;s payment, notify your insurer as well. Insurers have audit rights and financial incentives to correct overbilling. Your insurer&rsquo;s assistance can be a powerful lever against stubborn billing departments.</p>
  <h2>Where to go from here</h2>
  <p>See <a href="/guides/how-to-negotiate-hospital-bills">how to negotiate bills</a> and <a href="/guides/hospital-bill-misconceptions">common misconceptions</a>.</p>
</BaseLayout>
